# Welcome to {{ .ProjectName }}!

This project was bootstrapped with **Piko**, a Go-powered web framework for building fast, server-rendered websites with minimal client-side JavaScript.

This README will guide you through the essential commands and the structure of your new application.

---

## Getting started

You're just a few steps away from running your application.

### 1. Build your project for the first time

Before you can run the server, you need to run the Piko generator. This command compiles your `.pk` and `.pkc` files into optimised Go packages and JavaScript assets.

```bash
go run ./cmd/generator/main.go all
```
*You only need to run this once initially. The development server will handle re-builds for you after this.*

### 2. Start the development server

The best way to run your application during development is with `air`, which provides live reloading for both backend and frontend changes. Your project is already configured for it!

```bash
air
```

Your application will now be running at **http://localhost:8080** (or the next available port).

Navigate to this URL in your browser. You should see the "Welcome to Piko" page. Now, try editing `pages/index.pk` and watch your browser update automatically!

---

##  Scripts and commands

-   **`air`**: Starts the development server with live reloading. This is your primary command for development. It automatically re-runs the generator and rebuilds your main application when you save a file.

-   **`go run ./cmd/generator/main.go all`**: Manually runs the Piko asset generator. You'll need to run this as part of your build process for production deployments.

-   **`go run ./cmd/main/main.go`**: Starts the Piko web server without the live-reloading wrapper.

-   **`go run ./cmd/main/main.go prod`**: Starts the Piko web server in production mode.

-   **`piko fmt -w -r .`**: Formats all `.pk` template files in your project.

